    "# 🎙️ Speech Transcription & Audio Analysis\n",
    "\n",
    "**Author:** Marcio da Costa Oliveira  \n",
    "**GitHub:** [MARCIO-COSTA93](https://github.com/MARCIO-COSTA93)  \n",
    "**LinkedIn:** [marcio-costa-oliveira](https://linkedin.com/in/marcio-costa-oliveira)\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "## Overview\n",
    "\n",
    "This notebook demonstrates a complete pipeline for **speech-to-text transcription** using the `SpeechRecognition` library, with additional audio preprocessing and analysis techniques relevant to real-world voice applications.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Key features:\n",
    "- Multi-format audio support: WAV, OGG, OPUS, MP3, FLAC\n",
    "- Ambient noise adjustment for improved transcription accuracy\n",
    "- Data augmentation: noise injection and time stretching\n",
    "- Visual analysis: waveform and spectrogram before/after preprocessing\n",
    "- Comparison between online (Google Web Speech API) and offline (CMU Sphinx) recognition\n",
    "- Real-world use case: WhatsApp voice message transcription\n",
    "\n",
    "### Why this matters for KWS/ASR systems:\n",
    "Understanding how raw audio is preprocessed and transcribed is foundational for building **Keyword Spotting (KWS)** and **Automatic Speech Recognition (ASR)** pipelines. Techniques like noise adjustment and format normalization are essential steps before any deep learning model can reliably detect keywords or transcribe speech."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 1. Installing Dependencies"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# SpeechRecognition: main library for speech-to-text\n",
    "# PyAudio: required for microphone input\n",
    "# pydub: audio format conversion (OGG, MP3, etc.)\n",
    "# audiomentations: state-of-the-art audio data augmentation\n",
    "!pip install SpeechRecognition PyAudio pydub audiomentations\n",
    "!apt-get install -y ffmpeg  # required for format conversion"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 2. Importing Libraries"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import os\n",
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import librosa\n",
    "import librosa.display as ld\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "import soundfile as sf\n",
    "import speech_recognition as sr\n",
    "from pydub import AudioSegment\n",
    "from IPython.display import Audio, display\n",
    "from audiomentations import Compose, AddGaussianNoise, TimeStretch, PitchShift\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f'SpeechRecognition version: {sr.__version__}')\n",
    "print(f'librosa version: {librosa.__version__}')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 3. Audio Utility Functions\n",
    "\n",
    "Centralizing reusable functions is a best practice for maintainable ML pipelines."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def load_audio(file_path, target_sr=16000):\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    Load an audio file and resample to target sample rate.\n",
    "    \n",
    "    Why 16kHz? Most speech recognition models are trained on 16kHz audio.\n",
    "    Resampling ensures compatibility across different input sources.\n",
    "    \n",
    "    Args:\n",
    "        file_path (str): Path to audio file\n",
    "        target_sr (int): Target sample rate in Hz (default: 16000)\n",
    "    \n",
    "    Returns:\n",
    "        tuple: (audio_data, sample_rate)\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    data, sr = librosa.load(file_path, sr=target_sr)\n",
    "    print(f'File: {os.path.basename(file_path)}')\n",
    "    print(f'Sample rate: {sr} Hz')\n",
    "    print(f'Duration: {len(data)/sr:.2f}s')\n",
    "    print(f'Total samples: {len(data)}')\n",
    "    return data, sr\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "def plot_audio_analysis(data, sr, title='Audio Analysis'):\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    Plot waveform and spectrogram side by side.\n",
    "    \n",
    "    Waveform shows amplitude over time (energy of the signal).\n",
    "    Spectrogram shows frequency content over time — this is what\n",
    "    neural networks 'see' when processing audio.\n",
    "    \n",
    "    Args:\n",
    "        data (np.array): Audio waveform\n",
    "        sr (int): Sample rate\n",
    "        title (str): Plot title\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(14, 4))\n",
    "    fig.suptitle(title, fontsize=14, fontweight='bold')\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Waveform\n",
    "    axes[0].set_title('Waveform')\n",
    "    ld.waveshow(data, sr=sr, ax=axes[0])\n",
    "    axes[0].set_xlabel('Time (s)')\n",
    "    axes[0].set_ylabel('Amplitude')\n",
    "\n",
    "    # STFT Spectrogram\n",
    "    # STFT (Short-Time Fourier Transform) decomposes the signal into\n",
    "    # frequency components over time — essential for audio ML tasks\n",
    "    stft = librosa.stft(data)\n",
    "    stft_db = librosa.amplitude_to_db(np.abs(stft))\n",
    "    img = ld.specshow(stft_db, sr=sr, x_axis='time', y_axis='log', ax=axes[1])\n",
    "    axes[1].set_title('Spectrogram (STFT)')\n",
    "    fig.colorbar(img, ax=axes[1], format='%+2.0f dB')\n",
    "\n",
    "    plt.tight_layout()\n",
    "    plt.show()\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "def convert_to_wav(input_path, output_path=None):\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    Convert audio file to WAV format.\n",
    "    \n",
    "    SpeechRecognition natively supports WAV. Converting other formats\n",
    "    (OGG, OPUS, MP3) ensures compatibility with all recognition engines.\n",
    "    \n",
    "    Args:\n",
    "        input_path (str): Path to input audio file\n",
    "        output_path (str): Path to output WAV file (optional)\n",
    "    \n",
    "    Returns:\n",
    "        str: Path to the converted WAV file\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    ext = os.path.splitext(input_path)[1].lower().replace('.', '')\n",
    "    if output_path is None:\n",
    "        output_path = os.path.splitext(input_path)[0] + '_converted.wav'\n",
    "\n",
    "    format_map = {'ogg': 'ogg', 'opus': 'opus', 'mp3': 'mp3', 'flac': 'flac', 'wav': 'wav'}\n",
    "    audio_format = format_map.get(ext, 'wav')\n",
    "\n",
    "    audio = AudioSegment.from_file(input_path, format=audio_format)\n",
    "    audio.export(output_path, format='wav')\n",
    "    print(f'Converted {ext.upper()} → WAV: {output_path}')\n",
    "    return output_path"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 4. Data Augmentation\n",
    "\n",
    "Data augmentation artificially increases dataset diversity by applying transformations to existing audio. This is critical for building robust speech models that work in real-world conditions (background noise, different speaking speeds, etc.)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def apply_augmentation(data, sr, augmentation_type='all'):\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    Apply audio data augmentation techniques.\n",
    "    \n",
    "    Augmentation types:\n",
    "    - 'noise': Adds Gaussian noise — simulates real-world background noise\n",
    "    - 'stretch': Time stretching — simulates different speaking speeds\n",
    "    - 'pitch': Pitch shifting — simulates different voices/microphones\n",
    "    - 'all': Applies all transformations sequentially\n",
    "    \n",
    "    Args:\n",
    "        data (np.array): Audio waveform\n",
    "        sr (int): Sample rate\n",
    "        augmentation_type (str): Type of augmentation to apply\n",
    "    \n",
    "    Returns:\n",
    "        np.array: Augmented audio waveform\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    augmentations = {\n",
    "        'noise': Compose([AddGaussianNoise(min_amplitude=0.001, max_amplitude=0.015, p=1.0)]),\n",
    "        'stretch': Compose([TimeStretch(min_rate=0.8, max_rate=1.2, p=1.0)]),\n",
    "        'pitch': Compose([PitchShift(min_semitones=-4, max_semitones=4, p=1.0)]),\n",
    "        'all': Compose([\n",
    "            AddGaussianNoise(min_amplitude=0.001, max_amplitude=0.015, p=0.5),\n",
    "            TimeStretch(min_rate=0.8, max_rate=1.2, p=0.5),\n",
    "            PitchShift(min_semitones=-4, max_semitones=4, p=0.5)\n",
    "        ])\n",
    "    }\n",
    "\n",
    "    augment = augmentations.get(augmentation_type, augmentations['all'])\n",
    "    augmented = augment(samples=data, sample_rate=sr)\n",
    "    return augmented\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "def compare_augmentation(data, sr, augmentation_type='noise'):\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    Visualize original vs augmented audio side by side.\n",
    "    Useful for understanding the effect of each augmentation.\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    augmented = apply_augmentation(data, sr, augmentation_type)\n",
    "\n",
    "    fig, axes = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(14, 8))\n",
    "    fig.suptitle(f'Augmentation Comparison: {augmentation_type}', fontsize=14, fontweight='bold')\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Original waveform\n",
    "    ld.waveshow(data, sr=sr, ax=axes[0][0])\n",
    "    axes[0][0].set_title('Original - Waveform')\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Augmented waveform\n",
    "    ld.waveshow(augmented, sr=sr, ax=axes[0][1])\n",
    "    axes[0][1].set_title(f'Augmented ({augmentation_type}) - Waveform')\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Original spectrogram\n",
    "    stft_orig = librosa.amplitude_to_db(np.abs(librosa.stft(data)))\n",
    "    ld.specshow(stft_orig, sr=sr, x_axis='time', y_axis='log', ax=axes[1][0])\n",
    "    axes[1][0].set_title('Original - Spectrogram')\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Augmented spectrogram\n",
    "    stft_aug = librosa.amplitude_to_db(np.abs(librosa.stft(augmented)))\n",
    "    ld.specshow(stft_aug, sr=sr, x_axis='time', y_axis='log', ax=axes[1][1])\n",
    "    axes[1][1].set_title(f'Augmented ({augmentation_type}) - Spectrogram')\n",
    "\n",
    "    plt.tight_layout()\n",
    "    plt.show()\n",
    "\n",
    "    return augmented"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 5. Speech Recognition Engine\n",
    "\n",
    "Comparing online (Google) vs offline (Sphinx) recognition engines.\n",
    "In production KWS systems, offline recognition is preferred for privacy and latency."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Initialize recognizer\n",
    "# The Recognizer object manages audio input and interfaces with recognition APIs\n",
    "recognizer = sr.Recognizer()\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "def transcribe_audio(file_path, engine='google', language='pt-BR', adjust_noise=True, noise_duration=0.5):\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    Transcribe audio file using specified recognition engine.\n",
    "    \n",
    "    Args:\n",
    "        file_path (str): Path to audio file (WAV format)\n",
    "        engine (str): Recognition engine - 'google' (online) or 'sphinx' (offline)\n",
    "        language (str): Language code (e.g. 'pt-BR', 'en-US')\n",
    "        adjust_noise (bool): Whether to adjust for ambient noise before recognition\n",
    "        noise_duration (float): Duration in seconds used to sample ambient noise\n",
    "    \n",
    "    Returns:\n",
    "        str: Transcribed text or error message\n",
    "    \n",
    "    Note on noise adjustment:\n",
    "        adjust_for_ambient_noise() samples the first N seconds of audio to\n",
    "        estimate background noise level, then sets an energy threshold above\n",
    "        which audio is considered speech. This significantly improves accuracy\n",
    "        in noisy environments.\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    audio_file = sr.AudioFile(file_path)\n",
    "\n",
    "    with audio_file as source:\n",
    "        if adjust_noise:\n",
    "            # Calibrate for ambient noise — essential for real-world audio\n",
    "            recognizer.adjust_for_ambient_noise(source, duration=noise_duration)\n",
    "        audio_data = recognizer.record(source)\n",
    "\n",
    "    try:\n",
    "        if engine == 'google':\n",
    "            # Online: requires internet, high accuracy, supports many languages\n",
    "            result = recognizer.recognize_google(audio_data, language=language)\n",
    "        elif engine == 'sphinx':\n",
    "            # Offline: no internet required, works on embedded devices\n",
    "            # Lower accuracy but critical for privacy-sensitive applications\n",
    "            result = recognizer.recognize_sphinx(audio_data)\n",
    "        else:\n",
    "            result = 'Unknown engine. Use google or sphinx.'\n",
    "\n",
    "        print(f'[{engine.upper()}] Transcription: {result}')\n",
    "        return result\n",
    "\n",
    "    except sr.UnknownValueError:\n",
    "        print(f'[{engine.upper()}] Could not understand audio.')\n",
    "        return None\n",
    "    except sr.RequestError as e:\n",
    "        print(f'[{engine.upper()}] API error: {e}')\n",
    "        return None\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "def compare_engines(file_path, language='pt-BR'):\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    Compare transcription results from Google (online) vs Sphinx (offline).\n",
    "    Useful for evaluating trade-offs between accuracy and privacy/latency.\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    print('=' * 50)\n",
    "    print('ENGINE COMPARISON')\n",
    "    print('=' * 50)\n",
    "    print('\\n[GOOGLE - Online]')\n",
    "    google_result = transcribe_audio(file_path, engine='google', language=language)\n",
    "    print('\\n[SPHINX - Offline]')\n",
    "    sphinx_result = transcribe_audio(file_path, engine='sphinx')\n",
    "    print('\\nSummary:')\n",
    "    print(f'  Google : {google_result}')\n",
    "    print(f'  Sphinx : {sphinx_result}')\n",
    "    return google_result, sphinx_result"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 6. Multi-format Audio Processing\n",
    "\n",
    "Real-world applications deal with many audio formats. WhatsApp uses OGG/OPUS, podcasts use MP3, recordings use WAV or FLAC. This pipeline handles all of them."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def process_audio_file(file_path, language='pt-BR', show_analysis=True):\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    Full pipeline: load → convert → visualize → augment → transcribe.\n",
    "    \n",
    "    This function demonstrates the complete preprocessing pipeline\n",
    "    that would precede a keyword detection model in production.\n",
    "    \n",
    "    Args:\n",
    "        file_path (str): Path to audio file (any supported format)\n",
    "        language (str): Language code for transcription\n",
    "        show_analysis (bool): Whether to show waveform/spectrogram plots\n",
    "    \n",
    "    Returns:\n",
    "        str: Transcription result\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    ext = os.path.splitext(file_path)[1].lower()\n",
    "    print(f'Processing: {os.path.basename(file_path)} [{ext}]')\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Step 1: Convert to WAV if needed\n",
    "    if ext != '.wav':\n",
    "        wav_path = convert_to_wav(file_path)\n",
    "    else:\n",
    "        wav_path = file_path\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Step 2: Load and analyze\n",
    "    data, sample_rate = load_audio(wav_path)\n",
    "    display(Audio(data=data, rate=sample_rate))\n",
    "\n",
    "    if show_analysis:\n",
    "        plot_audio_analysis(data, sample_rate, title=f'Original: {os.path.basename(file_path)}')\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Step 3: Apply augmentation and compare\n",
    "    if show_analysis:\n",
    "        print('\\nApplying noise augmentation...')\n",
    "        augmented = compare_augmentation(data, sample_rate, augmentation_type='noise')\n",
    "\n",
    "        # Save augmented version for transcription comparison\n",
    "        aug_path = wav_path.replace('.wav', '_augmented.wav')\n",
    "        sf.write(aug_path, augmented, sample_rate)\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Step 4: Transcribe original\n",
    "    print('\\nTranscribing original audio...')\n",
    "    result = transcribe_audio(wav_path, language=language)\n",
    "\n",
    "    return result\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "# Example usage — replace with your own audio file path\n",
    "# process_audio_file('/content/audios/your_audio.wav', language='pt-BR')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 7. WhatsApp Voice Message Transcription\n",
    "\n",
    "A practical real-world use case: transcribing WhatsApp voice messages (OGG/OPUS format)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def transcribe_whatsapp_messages(audio_dir, language='pt-BR'):\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    Batch transcription of WhatsApp voice messages.\n",
    "    \n",
    "    WhatsApp uses OGG (Android) and OPUS (iOS) formats.\n",
    "    This function converts them to WAV and transcribes all at once.\n",
    "    \n",
    "    Args:\n",
    "        audio_dir (str): Directory containing audio files\n",
    "        language (str): Language code for transcription\n",
    "    \n",
    "    Returns:\n",
    "        dict: Filename -> transcription mapping\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    supported_formats = ['.ogg', '.opus', '.mp3', '.wav', '.flac']\n",
    "    results = {}\n",
    "\n",
    "    audio_files = [\n",
    "        f for f in os.listdir(audio_dir)\n",
    "        if os.path.splitext(f)[1].lower() in supported_formats\n",
    "    ]\n",
    "\n",
    "    print(f'Found {len(audio_files)} audio file(s) in {audio_dir}')\n",
    "    print('=' * 50)\n",
    "\n",
    "    for filename in audio_files:\n",
    "        file_path = os.path.join(audio_dir, filename)\n",
    "        print(f'\\nProcessing: {filename}')\n",
    "\n",
    "        ext = os.path.splitext(filename)[1].lower()\n",
    "        if ext != '.wav':\n",
    "            wav_path = convert_to_wav(file_path)\n",
    "        else:\n",
    "            wav_path = file_path\n",
    "\n",
    "        transcription = transcribe_audio(wav_path, language=language)\n",
    "        results[filename] = transcription\n",
    "\n",
    "    print('\\n' + '=' * 50)\n",
    "    print('TRANSCRIPTION RESULTS:')\n",
    "    for fname, text in results.items():\n",
    "        print(f'  {fname}: {text}')\n",
    "\n",
    "    return results\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "# Example usage:\n",
    "# results = transcribe_whatsapp_messages('/content/audios/', language='pt-BR')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 8. Noise Adjustment Analysis\n",
    "\n",
    "Demonstrating the impact of ambient noise adjustment on transcription accuracy."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def noise_adjustment_comparison(file_path, language='pt-BR'):\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    Compare transcription with and without ambient noise adjustment.\n",
    "    \n",
    "    This demonstrates why noise calibration matters:\n",
    "    - Without adjustment: recognizer may misinterpret silence/noise as speech\n",
    "    - With adjustment: energy threshold is calibrated to the actual environment\n",
    "    \n",
    "    This technique is directly applicable to keyword spotting systems,\n",
    "    where false positive detection (triggering on noise) is a key challenge.\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    print('Transcription WITHOUT noise adjustment:')\n",
    "    result_no_adjust = transcribe_audio(file_path, language=language, adjust_noise=False)\n",
    "\n",
    "    print('\\nTranscription WITH noise adjustment (duration=0.5s):')\n",
    "    result_with_adjust = transcribe_audio(file_path, language=language, adjust_noise=True, noise_duration=0.5)\n",
    "\n",
    "    print('\\nTranscription WITH noise adjustment (duration=1.0s):')\n",
    "    result_with_adjust_1s = transcribe_audio(file_path, language=language, adjust_noise=True, noise_duration=1.0)\n",
    "\n",
    "    print('\\nSummary:')\n",
    "    print(f'  No adjustment  : {result_no_adjust}')\n",
    "    print(f'  Adjusted (0.5s): {result_with_adjust}')\n",
    "    print(f'  Adjusted (1.0s): {result_with_adjust_1s}')\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "# Example usage:\n",
    "# noise_adjustment_comparison('/content/audios/your_audio.wav', language='pt-BR')"
   ]
  },
